THESE days it seems dieting has become a fashion trend.But what do you actually need to eat to be healthy.This month is Healthy Lifestyles Awareness Month in Mzansi so SunHealth turns the spotlight on healthy eating. if(typeof za24_DisplayAd != "undefined") za24_DisplayAd("300x250","2");<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a>A healthy lifestyle includes regular exercise, a healthy, nutritious diet and regular check-ups at your doctor.Gert Coetzee, pharmacist, diet pioneer and founder of The Diet Everyone Talks About, said cooking your own meals as often as possible, and using the healthiest and freshest ingredients is best to monitor what goes into your body. He said a good diet is important for overall health.Carbohydrates are responsible for raising blood sugar levels, so cutting down the amount of carbs you take in is key. The balance between how much insulin is in your body and the carbs you eat makes a big difference to your blood glucose levels.Recommended foods- Fibre helps control blood sugar levels – include nuts, vegetables, whole wheat, oatmeal and brown rice in your diet.- Fish is a good substitute for high-fat meats – include tuna and sardines.- Vegetables are full of vitamins, fibre and minerals, and don’t contain many kilojoules and carbohydrates – include broccoli, carrots, celery, cucumber, mushrooms and peppers.- Foods that contain polyunsaturated and monounsaturated fats help lower your cholesterol levels – include avocados, almonds, walnuts and olives. - Leafy greens help your kidneys get rid of sodium, lowering blood pressure – include kale and spinach.- Potatoes are high in potassium and magnesium which help lower your blood pressure.- Researchers at Barts and The London School of Medicine have discovered that drinking 500ml of beetroot juice a day can reduce blood pressure.- Skim milk is an excellent source of calcium and is low in fat – important for a high-blood pressure diet.